    { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Orange County" },
    { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Ventura County" },
    { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "San Bernardino County" },
    { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Riverside County" }
  ],
  "offers": {
    "@type": "Offer",
    "priceSpecification": {
      "@type": "PriceSpecification",
      "price": "120.00",
      "priceCurrency": "USD",
      "description": "Commercial diagnostic fee, applied toward repair"
    }
  }
})} />

<script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does commercial exhaust hood repair cost?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Our commercial diagnostic fee is $120, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most exhaust hood repairs run between $180 and $650. Exhaust fan motor replacement, belt replacement, bearing repair, speed control, or baffle filter cleaning/replacement is toward the mid-range. Full blower assembly replacement, MUA (make-up air) unit work, or ductwork repair runs higher. We provide a written estimate before any work begins. Note: NFPA 96 hood cleaning (grease duct cleaning) is a separate service from mechanical repair — cleaning services run $300–$800 depending on hood size and duct length."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Which areas of Southern California do you cover?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "All five SoCal counties: Los Angeles, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside. We dispatch from 8 service territories — West Hollywood, LA, Beverly Hills, Pasadena, Thousand Oaks, Irvine, Rancho Cucamonga, and Temecula — so the technician on your hood call is coming from the closest one. Hood failures over active cooking equipment are emergency priority dispatch in every county."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between a Type I and Type II commercial exhaust hood?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Type I hoods are required over cooking equipment that produces grease-laden vapors — fryers, griddles, open burners, charbroilers, woks. They must include grease filters or baffle filters, a grease collection system, and in California, a fire suppression system. NFPA 96 governs Type I installations and requires periodic cleaning by a certified service. Type II hoods are used over equipment producing heat, steam, and odors without significant grease — steamers, dishwashers, ovens without open flame. They require less stringent construction and do not mandate fire suppression. The repair approach differs significantly between the two."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you also repair make-up air units (MUA)?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Hood + MUA is a paired system — every CFM the exhaust hood pulls out has to be replaced by tempered make-up air, or the kitchen goes into negative pressure (back-drafts down chimneys, doors that won't open, gas appliances starving for combustion air). MUA failure typically presents as 'exhaust seems weak even though the fan is fine' or 'kitchen smells like outside air dust.' We service MUA fans, gas burners (heated MUA), evaporative coolers (cooled MUA), filters, and damper actuators. EPA and CSLB licensing covers both the exhaust and supply sides of the system."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My restaurant exhaust hood is not pulling air — what should I check first?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Check the baffle or grease filters first. Severely grease-loaded filters reduce airflow dramatically — in a busy kitchen, filters can accumulate enough grease in 2–4 weeks to significantly reduce ventilation effectiveness. Second, check whether the make-up air unit (MUA) is running. If MUA is down and exhaust is up, the kitchen goes into negative pressure and exhaust output collapses regardless of fan condition. Third, if filters are clean and MUA is running, the issue is in the exhaust fan motor, belt, bearings, or ductwork — call us at (424) 325-0520."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is a broken commercial exhaust hood a fire code violation?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A non-functioning exhaust hood over cooking equipment that produces grease-laden vapors (Type I application) is a fire code violation under NFPA 96 and California Fire Code, enforced by local fire authority (LAFD, OCFA, Ventura County Fire, San Bernardino County Fire, Riverside County Fire). Cooking over open flame or a fryer without functioning exhaust ventilation allows grease vapor to accumulate in the kitchen and ductwork — a serious fire risk. Inspectors can cite this as a violation and require correction before the kitchen can operate. We treat exhaust hood failures over active cooking equipment as emergency priority calls."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you repair Captive-Aire, Gaylord, Halton, and Greenheck commercial exhaust hoods and fans?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Captive-Aire, Gaylord, and Halton are the three most common commercial exhaust hood brands across SoCal restaurant kitchens. We also service Accurex, Streivor, and custom-fabricated stainless steel hoods. On the fan side: Greenheck (CUE/CUBE upblast), Loren Cook, Twin City Fan, and Captive-Aire integrated fans. For residential and semi-commercial range hoods (Broan, Vent-A-Hood, Viking, Wolf range hoods), we service those as well — see our residential range hood repair service."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often does a commercial exhaust hood need service?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "NFPA 96 Standard Table 11.4 sets cleaning intervals based on cooking volume: monthly for solid-fuel cooking and 24-hour operations, quarterly for high-volume restaurants (charbroilers, woks), semi-annually for moderate-volume full-service restaurants, and annually for low-volume operations (small bars, light cooking). Mechanical service (fan motor inspection, bearing lubrication, belt check, MUA test, speed control verification) should be performed annually or when problems are detected. Many operators schedule cleaning and mechanical service on the same visit."
      }
    }
  ]
})} />

